<Content>$12.95 to use the refrigerator I was the only member of our 3-person group to have had the pleasure of traveling to Puerto Rico on three prior vacations (twice via cruise and once as a guest at The Ritz Carlton Hotel). In addition, I was celebrating my birthday on July 4th 鈥?so you can imagine that our 5-day get-a-way was highly anticipated. Unfortunately, excitement quickly turned to disappointment and disbelief during our check-in process on July 3, 2008. Please note: It鈥檚 always a bad sign when upon your arrival you provide the hotel representative with the last name of your party and while reviewing their computer screen they give you the friendly 鈥榦h dear鈥?grin. This is how we were greeted by the hotel rep. After excusing himself to 鈥渃heck on something鈥?for 5-minutes, he returned and explained that the hotel room we reserved months prior (and been charged an additional $350 for a third person) was unavailable for that evening. It was also explained that reserving a room does not guarantee its availability. I鈥檝e been blessed to travel the U.S. and various countries on several continents and I can honestly say that I am still dumbfounded by that ridiculous statement. We were then told that they could set-up an air mattress in a room that we would stay in temporarily for the evening until a room became available 鈥渟ometime鈥?tomorrow on July 4th. Did I mention that July 4th was my birthday? I explained that we did not rearrange our thriving careers, client/patient needs or family obligations to travel to Puerto Rico and sleep on an air mattress. The thought and verbal suggestion was insulting. Last time I checked this wasn鈥檛 The Holiday Inn, Best Western or Budget Inn, especially not for what they charge. If I鈥檓 not mistaken the El San Juan Hotel  Casino proudly boasts that they are members of LXR Luxury Resorts. Needless to say that suggestion was quickly dismissed. It was then explained that the only room available to accommodate our party 鈥榝or the evening鈥?was on the second floor in another part of the hotel; it was explained that the room had a queen size bed and a sleeper sofa.The second floor is not part of the renovated hotel. It does not even register as a designated floor in the main elevators. The second floor is a separate wing of the hotel 鈥?the older section that has yet to be renovated. The staff of the El San Juan Hotel  Casino should have been embarrassed to even provide any guest(s) with keys to this dilapidated structure. Youth hostiles in Europe are more appeasing. The room was hideous and filthy. If we were a group of high school students on a senior trip or on Spring Break with no culture, tact, class or fear of communicable disease, then maybe the room may have been appealing. As three successful professional women 鈥?I think not! There were rembrandts of food and broken glass on the carpet. The bathroom was completely unsanitary. After calling the front desk a member of the housekeeping staff visited our room and agreed with our assessment: He quickly left the room to retrieve a vacuum. At this point enough was enough. We returned to the lobby and respectfully requested that the hotel locate the room which we had originally booked months prior, the beautiful room that adorns the hotel website. And like magic a room was available. We were given a choice of a room on the 3rd or 7th floor 鈥?same size, different layout. Unfortunately, it was explained to us that an air mattress would not fit in the room. At that point in our 3-hour excursion of finding an appropriate and need I say sanitary room 鈥?we agreed on the 7th floor room which was equal to what perspective guests view on the website. What was truly disappointing was the obvious presence of senior management who stood by an observed or dissatisfaction during our numerous trips to the front desk and NEVER, not once, did they interject to introduce themselves or at the very least offer apologies to their hotel guests who were noticeably disappointed with their 3-hour introduction to the El San Juan Hotel  Casino. Needless to say, the remaining parts of our vacation were enjoyable. However, as a whole we were yet again dumfounded during our check-out process. Due to our extended stay and keeping in fashion with other hotel guests, we frequented the local grocery store and purchased beverages and fruits in lieu of paying the hefty price and indulging in the stocked mini-bar provided in our hotel room. Color us very surprised when a fee of $12.95 was charged to our final bill. When we inquired about the charge we were told, 鈥淚t鈥檚 for the use of the refrigerator鈥? Shame on you El San Juan Hotel  Casino! In all my years of traveling I have never been charged for the use of the complimentary refrigerator. We used the iron as well, was that additional charge an oversight on the hotels鈥?part? This hotel boasts their membership with LXR Luxury Results. The El San Juan Hotel  Casino should take a lesson in etiquette from the Ritz Carlton, The Montage, Atlantis Resort, MGM, The Bellagio, and Caesars Palace to name a few regarding truly luxurious accomodations. 
