<Author>BizVacationTrvler
<Content>A Pricey Facade but would still recommend After much research I finally chose the El San Juan for a 2 night get away from NYC. Most other hotels are random beach inns that would just be looking for trouble. Other mainstream hotels got to many mixed reviews. (Obviously the Intercontinental or Ritz certainly would be great options if you鈥檙e willing to pay.)The El San Juan is esthetically gorgeous, the lobby is very well done and the rooms (in the main tower) are bright and comfy. The air conditioning def pumps out cold air so the blankets come in handy and add a cozy feeling. The tile floors did get cold though鈥nd they could have been much cleaner. Housekeeping only goes over them with a Swiffer! The room was huge鈥? Queen beds and a large sitting area. The beds were plush and comfy. Regarding bed bugs鈥 didn鈥檛 have an issue. I assume the few mosquito bites were from the pool and rainforest tour.There are signs all over the lobby regarding attire after 7pm. It鈥檚 to keep the nightclub feel consistent. Great vibe if you鈥檙e looking to just hang out for a few drinks and listen to music. Be aware, drinks will cost ya plenty!Look on the hotel website for specials. We got a midweek special, $150 a night. Which is very reasonable for this hotel and all of it鈥檚 amenities. Plus a $50 credit (would have been $75 if we stayed another night). The credit was put towards dinner at Koco鈥檚 which was delicious. All the hotel restaurants were over priced. (The Palm was pricier in the hotel than in NYC. The Ranch, a roof top restaurant, with a tex Mex theme was great鈥ncluding the mechanical bull. A few menus with prices are on the website. The Breakfast Buffet was $26...no matter how good, Omelets should not cost that much!!! (go down the block to Edith's Caf茅 for great local food鈥t鈥檚 like a Puerto Rican diner in a shopping center with other fast food chains.) There鈥檚 also a major 24 hour supermarket, Pueblo鈥檚, around the corner for anything you鈥檒l need鈥hey sell alcohol which I saw people bringing to the pool. (since those fun fruity looking daiquiris and mojitos are $10.50)The pool(s) ARE the main attraction to this hotel. If you鈥檙e looking for RR this is the spot!! You鈥檒l need to get up early to get those fancy bed cabanas (by 8am or 6:30 during spring break!). Late comers will get a lounge or even pushed out to the beach! (HINT: Tip the pool staff to ensure a good spot 鈥?go down early and put a book/empty bag and towel and they鈥檒l look out that no one moves it while you get breakfast and ready for the day!) The pools were clean and cleaned every morning with pumps. Security is also very tight! So no one will be wondering in from the public beach. Hotel guests get a colored bracelet.Wave runners/Jet skies are $70 for 30 minutes. Not worth it.I took a tour of the rain forest that the hotel set up. I wanted more of a hike but the guy at the desk really didn鈥檛 know much more than what was written in the book. They鈥檙e just there to make a reservation. But for $70 is was worth it since I didn鈥檛 have to worry about renting a car, directions, parking, etc.The only real issue is that the hotel restaurants are very expensive with no other choices. The hotel was a $21 cab ride to Old San Juan. We would have rented a car but that鈥檚 an additional $16 a night to park at the hotel. It was only $12.50 from the airport鈥hich is a 5 minute ride across the express way.Next time, I鈥檒l stay at El Convento in Old San Juan with better access to explore the island. If you鈥檙e looking for modern sexy hotel, some RR at the pool and money is no issue for dinner鈥hen you鈥檒l love the El San Juan. 
