<Content>Had a great time...don't let other reviews scare you I just came back from the El San Juan last night and had read a good number of the review prior to my departure. I was there with my friend, we are both in our late 20s.I had a great experience. Yes, we could not check-in until 4:00, that is their policy, nothing you can do...we accepted it and moved on. Checked our luggage, changed into our bathing suits in the lobby bathroom and hit the pool until the room was ready. Not a big deal.We had a Garden Lenai room, it was clean and huge. No bed bugs, no mildew. It was totally fine.The service at the bars was definitely slow. I didn't think people went out of their way to make sure you were being taken care of, but I felt that way about a lot of places we went in San Juan. I think it could be a cultural thing compared to other island/countries I have visited. No one was rude to us when they were helping us, however.You definitely need to get out early and get your lounge chairs. They do fill up quickly and I will agree that there may not be enough in comparison to how many people the hotel is able to accomodate. There were always chairs available on the beach, which we had to default to twice. Again, you're sitting on a white sand beach on a tropical island as opposed to poolside...it's a rough life. We still went in the pool even though our chairs were on the beach and vice versa on the days we had poolside chairs.Food at the hotel is expensive for sure, but not unexpected since most resorts are sort of like that. Pretty much New York prices on things, which is what I am used to. We did eat lunch there a few times. We started eating outside of the hotel for breakfast and dinner. If you walk towards the Ritz on the main road there is a great Puerto Rican restaurant, the food and service were great and it had a good atmosphere. We also went into Old San Juan at night for dinner, there are a lot of great places. Cab ride was about 15 - 20 dollars. I like to venture out of the hotel for things, so I didn't need to eat at the hotel every day for every meal. I don't think the El San Juan should be compared to the Ritz, that is a different class of hotel. You get what you pay for. I thought the hotel was hip, the bars were cool. The crowd was good for us singles, not a huge amount of families with small children. It was a great getaway in a beautiful place. When you travel you have to be able to roll with the punches and it seemed like some of the past reviews were a bit picky about minor things. But again, different people have different expectations. 
