<Author>dieselcone
<Content>five star price - third class service The front door of the lobby should have been our first clue on the quality of the hotel itself. If the first thing I see it that dirty and disgusting what about all the other things I can't see. I would like to comment on my last stay from July 14 Sat to July 17 Tues at the el San Juan hotel in Puerto Rico. I thought I was staying at a five star hotel instead I ending staying at a sub par hotel under a construction mess. First the rooms were not what we expected, if I wanted to stay in an ultra modern overprice trendy hotel I would have gone to Miami. My son who is only seven noticed all the dust bunnies under both beds when he dropped a toy. Unacceptable for a five star hotel. Smoking free environment not true, our floor smelled like cigarettes the entire time we were there. At night you had several people smoking by the cabanas. Ashes and butts everywhere. The next morning all the cushions were dirty with cigarette ashes. Poolside was also a disaster, my mom fell on the wet pavement and not even one employee came over to see how she was. They continued to take amongst themselves at the pool bar. I have never seen a dirtier pool area. Food on the floor, birds flying in and out of the area and cups and dishes under the chairs. Only one hot tub worked, the others were dirt and smelled like eggs. My husband pointed out that they did not have a working filter. Water and sand all over the cushions and floor. When is the last time those pools were cleaned? The bathrooms poolside were also not cleaned. Second the dress code in the lobby applies to only the hotel guest? Since when does the El San Juan hotel allow jeans, flip flops, tank tops and riff raf into the lobby. When we entered the casino on Sunday night you had a guy in his pjs with a ball cap on sideways playing on the slot machines. Where is the dress code? I overheard a conversion from another guest on his cell phone demanding his travel agent get him the hell out of this third class hotel and book him immediately into the Ritz Carlton when he saw who was allowed into the casino and lobby. He was dressed in a suit and his wife in a dress. I felt overdress and uncomfortable surrounded by an underdressed crowd. The young crowd you have attracted to your hotel is not suited for a luxury hotel. By the way I am only 36 years old but I did not want to hang out in the hotel lobby with underdressed 20-25 years olds. I could not even enjoy the pool area with all these couples all over each other in the middle of the day in front of my kids. The service was unacceptable as well. I paid $125.00 for lunch at poolside yet the couple sitting next to us was getting free food from their friend ( a waitress), she could not give them free drinks because they had an incident on Saturday 7/14 and were being watched closing. Totally unacceptable. Please remind all your employees that guests might also know how to speak Spanish. We tried to call several areas of the hotel. First we tried to call the spa on Sunday at 7.30pm to make an appointment for Monday and we told by your front desk well sometimes they close up early. We called room service that did not arrived until 1hr and 45 minutes with melted ice cream that we had to send back. We called the valet for our bags on check out day twice because the first guy we spoke to went on break and forgot to tell the next guy that we were waiting for our bags at 10.30am. The doors to the lobby totally disgusting, so dirty, I did not even want to place my hands anywhere. Your casino has also gone down hill. Sunday night 7/15 we were at the blackjack table and your dealer did not speak a word to us. After we won our money back, we got up from the table and made our way to the lobby and meet other guests who commented on your unfriendly staff. The heat was also unbearable due to the black out that night, the ac was not working properly. Monday night 7/16 we were at the roulette table with my parents and again the lady working the table said nothing to us but continued to gossip with the other guy at the next table. Needless to say when we won $140 we left because who wants to sit there and spend money when your staff does not even interact with your guests. The service at the casino again just as bad as everywhere else. 45 minutes we waited at the blackjack table on Sunday to get one drink. You have one girl for the entire floor. And believe me the casino floor was not crowded. When we checked out on Tuesday morning there was a Italian gentlemen arguing with the front desk woman and the manager at the front desk about his stay. He apparently hurt himself during your blackout and had not received any attention from your staff. He wanted to check out and insisted he wanted to pay cash. The woman at the front desk said you already have a credit card on file, let us just charge you on that (in English) he responded no I want to pay cash and remove my card from your records. The other woman said to her in Spanish  do not fight with him just charge him what ever and then we will load up his credit card later. I spoke to him and told him to be careful when we got his credit card bill. I had fond memories of the OLD El San Juan hotel, the place was a first class hotel. Now it longer lives up to its name. I will make sure to tell everyone I know that this hotel is no longer what it used to be. If you want to pay like a five star hotel but be surrounded by third class service and people then it is the place for you. Your staff no longer cares for your guests. Your management no longer cares for your guests. Making money seems to be the only thing this hotel cares about. dieselcone@msn.com 
