<Content>Good and bad My daughter (15) and I stayed at the ESJ for three nights at the beginning of April.Lobby is very nice, but had the smell of a bar all the time - don't know if it was the cleaning solution to clean up or something else. It smelled like a frat house.We stayed in a renovated room, which I don't know if we would have gotten if I hadn't been a pest about it from the time I made the reservation to the time we got there. The check-in was long, as the woman typed away at her keyboard for what seemed like hours. We still had to wait 3 hours for our room. I heard you could tip the front desk to get a renovated room, but I refused to do that. I think the woman was waiting for it though.The room was fine, but there was no full length mirror, no balcony. Beds were very comfortable. For a new room, it still had scuff marks on the walls, signs of wear and tear. Walls were paper thin and I was awakened at 5am by loud talking, blaring TV. Eventually had to call security after banging on the wall was ineffective. The pool area and pools were beautiful. But the biggest problem was that the beds with canopies were free Saturday and Sunday, but come Monday they instituted a $150 charge for their use. For the $150, you received water, a fruit basket and 2 bar drinks, along with the use of the beds. Not worth it and most went unoccupied or familes with children rented them because they couldn't get a regular chair. The biggest problem was just that -- getting a chair. I had to get down there at 7am to even get one, and I witnessed chair wars and difficult, obnoxious people each day. A woman tried to pick a fight with me by claiming my chair was hers and that she had held it and 2 next to it with magazines and towels. I told her the chair was empty and then pointed out that she actually held the chairs in the next row, but she refused to admit she saved those particular chairs because the cushions were smaller. She wound up writing a nasty review of the chair guy because he told her she was wrong and he had saved the two chairs next to me for someone else. I do know that if you paid off one of the pool guys they would save you a chair, but I saw people taking reserved chairs anyway. This was ridiculous. Who wants to get up early on vacation to get a chair! There should be a policy about this, as many chairs were saved and no one showed up all day!Pool food was good, but expensive. Bar drinks were $10.Area around the hotel was pretty grungy and commercial. Not pretty at all, but the grounds of the hotel were nice and private.Some staff were very friendly, others, like front desk, were not. Would I go back? Probably not, as I would prefer to see other places in the world and stay in nicer hotels. 
