<Author>ADCS
<Content>Ambilent About the Accommodations The 4-Star Rated El San Juan Hotel and Casino in Isla Verde (San Juan) Puerto RicoAmbivalent About the AcommodationsJune 24, 2006By: A Trumbull, CT Family TravelerMy husband and 12-year old twins, and two other familes decided to arrive San Juan one to two days prior to our cruise ship departure in order to ensure a relaxed arrival and some time to unwind. We, and one family, had never been to Puerto Rico and the other family of 5 had stayed at a Marriot Resort a year or two before and had a wonderful time. That family had accolades for their experience at that Marriot Resort. Anyway, since we wanted to be relatively close to Old San Juan and the pier, we narrowed down our choices to the Marriott Sellaris, The Hilton Carribe and the Wyndham El San Juan and the Ritz-Carlton ALL of the on-line reviews were mixed for these four hotels and our travel agent said to go with the San Juan as she had stayed there before. (We were surprised about the mixed review of the Ritz-Carlton.) So, since we liked the idea that the El San Juan not only had a couple of pools, it also had one of the larger beaches plus the casino. For one night, we needed simply a standard room, non-smoking, two double beds ($425 a night) and the larger family confirmed TWO standard ADJOINING non-smoking rooms as they had a 16-, 8-, and 9-year old. Rosemarie, John and their 18-year old son arrived a day prior to us and had no difficulties. We arrived around 2 p.m., checked in, and left our bags in their storage area. The family of 5 had problems: There was only one room booked! They had their AmEx bill with them and showed the clerk that TWO rooms had been paid for. The hotel was very crowded, service was slow. It took about an hour to straighten out the mess, but they were still trying to find another room anywhere for our friends. Hungry and getting late, we decided to eat lunch overlooking the pool area. There were no other diners and we were seated immediately. Our drinks came quickly and we placed our orders (hamburgers, salads - the basics). It took close to 45 minutes to get lunch and it was somewhat expensive for what we ordered - 4 adults and 5 kids. Just a meal and a soda or water. No coffee, no desserts. Anyway, we got our bags and went to our room. It was warm, the A/C wasn't working and a ceiling tile was removed exposing wires. Just as we were about to call, two hotel personnel came in and called down to the desk to get our room changed. One informed us that she had previously alerted the desk staff that this room was under renovation and not to be used. My twins and I went to the pool and, an hour later!! my husband joined us as it took that long to find us a room. Our family of 5 friends FINALLY got two rooms but they were on two different floors! Being in the lobby, we could see many others who had arrived were having similar problems. The next morning, from 6:30 a.m. to 7:00 a.m., we were awakened by a loud, non-stop buzzing as if a construction crew had started working. It was Sunday and when I called the front desk to alert them, they said it wasn't construction and other guests had called and Security was handling it. The sound stopped shortly afterward, resumed briefly and finally stopped completely. Starting around that time we also heard planes taking off from the airport as the hotel is only about 5 or 10 minutes away and the flight pattern goes over the hotel. I had called the hotel directly when we booked and asked if there was any airplane noise and received a vague answer of not really. We really can't complain about airplane noise as we were fully aware of the hotel's location in relation to the airport and we decided to stay anyway. Be aware, this might really bother people staying here more than one night. Yes, the hotel, old but beautiful, under renovation according to staff, was charming and convenient. The pools and beach very nice. By the way, once the lobby cleared, I quietly asked the desk clerk if something could be done since we had been polite, quite and patient regarding our rooms. The manager sent us 2 free breakfast vouchers for the next day. NOTE: Breakfast buffet was $25 per person. Even with the 2 vouchers, we didn't feel like spending $50 for breakfast for the twins. We asked the Conceriege for a breakfast recommendation in Old San Juan that opened early. We and the family of 5, took a cab into Old San Juan; enjoyed a standard American type breakfast which amounted to about $25 for the 4 of us and about $30 for the other 5 . The restaurant was clean and service was quick. (At the hotel, they would have spent $125 for breakfast before tip.) We did some touring of Old San Juan and the Fort before heading back to the hotel to check out at noon and head for the pier. After vacation, Rosemarie checked her AmEx bill and found out the hotel had double billed them . . . We didn't hate the hotel/service, but we all agreed that if staying in San Juan again we would try another hotel next time. 
