<Content>Mixed review of the Wyndham ESJ My wife and I just returned from a week at the Wyndham ESJ and had a mixed experience. I will provide a quick review of the positives and negatives:Check-in: PoorWe arrived at 5:00 PM and were told by the front desk clerk that our room wasn't ready yet, despite the fact that check-in was listed at 4:00 PM. The clerk took my cell phone number and told me that he would call us as soon as the room was ready. After 45 minutes and no call, I called to find out what was going on and the same clerk put me on hold for five minutes. I called back and asked to speak with the front desk manager, and presto, the clerk picked up the phone and told me that our room was ready and a key was promptly produced.Room: Below averageI concur with the other posters who said that the rooms were shabby. Our room (818), while clean, had a moldy smell and the carpet was worn in several places. The rooms could really use an upgrade. People considering this hotel should also note that a busy airport runway is located only a few hundred yards away from the hotel and during peak air traffic hours, the noise can be deafening. Maid service was prompt and reliable. The room was always cleaned by mid-afternoon. In summary, I expect a much nicer room for $275/night (all-in). Pool: ExcellentThe pool area is fantastic. The grounds are clean and well-maintained. The pool waitstaff is friendly and attentive, but never pushy. I often brought my own beer to the pool and was never hassled. My only complaint about the pool is that bad music was constantly being played at a high volume - it sounded like soft porn music. We asked the staff to turn it down a couple of times and they complied. The ocean beach is also nice and located just outside the pool area.Casino and Bar: ExcellentThis is what makes the Wyndham ESJ worth the money. On Thursday-Saturday, the stunning lobby, bars and casino explode with music, dancing and action. I really can't describe it - you need to see it to believe it. We were playing Blackjack next to Derek Jeter one night. We also bumped into Governor Pataki (NY) in the lobby.Restaurants: GoodThe Japanese place (Yamato) is very good and the teppanyaki chefs are entertaining. The food is decent at the poolside cafe and Palm is a solid steakhouse. These places are all very pricey - nine bucks for a rum punch! Go across the street and try Mi Casita and Metropole for reasonable, authentic Puerto Rican and Cuban fare, respectively.Gym: ExcellentPlently of treadmills and a nice assortment of machines and free weights. We had a really good vacation, but the next time, I will probably stay at the Intercontinental (for a nicer, less expensive room) and party at the Wyndhan ESJ. 
