<Author>keysgirl
<Content>Mixed Review We just returned from our vacation in Puerto Rico. The last 3 days we spent at the Wyndham El San Juan Hotel and Casino. We were travelling with 4 adults and 7 children (ages 16, 14, 14, 12, 10, 10, 9). Our overall opinion of the hotel was mixed. We arrived at the hotel at 7:30 PM after a full day at the Camuy Caverns. We were all in comfortable clothing (shorts, sandals, etc.). Boy did we feel underdressed when we walked into the lobby of this hotel. Maybe it was because of this that we were checked in VERY quickly! Our friend was parking the car, so 2 of the kids (16 and 14) sat in the lobby right by the Front Desk to wait on him so they could show him to the room. While they were waiting, a Security Guard came up and told them they had to leave because of their attire - their is a strict dress code after 7 PM in the lobby. They explained that they were waiting for their dad. The Security Guard said they had 5 minutes and then they had to leave. Thank goodness their dad walked up just after the Security Guard. The rooms are definitely not up to the Wyndham standards that I am used to. We had a great view of the pool and the ocean. One great safety concern that I had was the fact the the sliding glass door opened VERY EASILY and although there was a concrete railing on the other side of the door, it would not take anything for a child to open the door. The bathrooms were VERY small (just big enough for 1 person) and definitely showed signs of age!!!!! Our bathroom had plaster falling off the ceiling, and the bathtub / shower enclosure was so narrw that if you had a weight problem you might not have been able to use it. The bathtub had been recovered and their was water trapped underneath it. When you stepped in you felt as if you were on a waterbed. We called Engineering, who came up quickly, slit the plastic cover to release the water and glued it up. However, the next morning it was back to the way it was before. Due to the fact that the door to the bathroom had slats in it - there was NO PRIVACY whatsoever. As for sound proofing in the rooms - there was none. You could clearly hear EVERYTHING that was going on in the rooms around you. My daughter and 2 other teenage girls we were traveling with all had to share a room since they only allowed 4 people in a room and they have no roll-away beds available. They were on the same floor as us, but a few rooms down. When I asked why they were so tired the second day, they said that they were up all night because the people next door were having sex all night long. They got to listen to moaning, groaning, and the bed banging on the wall! Then the room on the other side of them had a little baby who cried all night long! This is not exactly something the front desk could do anything about! The lobby was gorgeous - with wood and chandeliers everywhere! And it came alive at night! There was live bands, Salsa dancing, a man rolling hand made cigars, and of course - the casino! The food was mixed. We ate at the Italian Restaurant on night and had a fabulous dinner! The service was great and the food was wonderful. We ordered dessert from Room Service one night and were terribly disappointed and it was very expensive - $25 for 3 pieces. The Carrot Cake was dry, as was the triple layer cake and the Flan was rubbery. The Deli in the Galleria was very expensive - $14.95 for a cheeseburger and $12.95 for a Tuna Sandwich. The pool and the beach are fabulous! Overall, the lobby is beautiful, the casino is fun, the entertainment is great, but the rooms (which is what you are paying $225 per night and up for) were a total disappointment. 
