<Content>Great place to visit, but.... Just got back from 5 nights celebrating a friends birthday. The good: Hotel lobby is beautiful (old world opulence and charm). Great scene in the lobby on Friday and Saturday nights. Most of the restaurants are suprisingly good for a hotel. Casino is friendly to veterans and novices alike. Most of the staff is helpful and friendly,  Pool and beach area is very nice (their beach is nicer that the one at the Ritz Carlton).The bad: Rooms are old and in serious need of updating. The two rooms I saw had large wet spots (2' diameter) on the rug from air conditioner condensation which gave them a musty/moldy smell (we were told there was nothing they could do to fix the problem). Bedspreads had miscellaneous stains on them (I don't want to know). Poor soundproofing- you can hear conversations in the neighboring rooms, phones ringing, room service and maid carts moving down the halls, vacuuming (at 7am) and of course the airplanes. My room actually vibrated from pipes whenever the room above used their shower or opened their closet slider! We were all supposed to get upgraded and were told they were unavailable because the hotel was sold out (I called a reservation line and found this to be a lie). My friends used the spa- massage  manicure and were overcharged even though they presented a buy one service get one at half price coupon all guests were given at the pool.  Unable to get into my room until 4:30pm (suprising because check-out is at noon and it is almost impossible to get a late check-out).Lastly, when I checked out, the woman at the front desk never even asked how was your stay, etc. - a basic customer service question.In summary: With some renovations and more attention to customer service, this hotel can be restored to its former grandeur. If you can get by the above issues, enjoy. If not, stay somewhere else and visit on a Friday or Saturday night for great people-watching. 
