<Content>Hip Lobby -- Disgusting Rooms Stayed at the WESJ after a 7 day cruise and have to say that most reviews of this hotel hit the nail right on the head. While the lobby seems to be an epicenter for activity in San Juan, the rooms appear not to have been renovated since Freido Corleone's days. They're quite simply dated - with a popcorn ceiling right above the shower and toilets similar to those I used back in grammar school in the 70's (with a big industrial metal flush). The biggest problem involving the rooms, however, is the fact that they're filthy. The first room we we're given was too dirty to describe (plus it was a handicapped room and we didn't want that -- my wife and I are 35 and in good shape). When we complained, they moved us to a room which, at first glance, appeared to be decent. But the filth of the rooms runs deep and what you don't catch at first glance you'll surely discover maybe an hour or two later. The bedsheets, as it turned out, we're covered in filth -- blood and other stains. Plus, they were infested with fleas -- we got bit from head to toe. The a/c unit dripped water constantly right into the middle of the room leaving a big puddle (I kid you not). The soundproofing for these rooms is simply ridiculous -- even had all the other problems not occurred, it would have been impossible to get a night's sleep at this hotel. We heard everything happening on our floor (the 8th) the entire night. When we complained to hotel management of these problems and notified them that we wanted to leave early they charged us $75 for early departure. While I realize that we had booked via the internet and chosen the non-refundable rate, I had no idea what kind of hellish room we would be getting. I chose the non-refundable rate with the understanding that the room we would be getting would be of a certain resort standard. The room we received barely met cheap motel standards and the $75 charged to be allowed to leave this dump-with-a-beautiful-lobby is asinine. Do yourself a favor and check yourself in at the Ritz -- it's where we moved to and we were quite happy with our accomodations. If we ever visit PR again (doubtful) I would only consider the Ritz or the El Convento Hotel in Old San Juan (we stayed there 1 night before our 7 day cruise). 
