<Content>Security staff out of control OUT OF CONTROL staff caused an inexcusable scene at the pool the second day of our stay. My brother and I decided to get a bagel, OJ and coffee from a nearby bakery that featured healthy breakfasts. Since it was a gorgeous morning we decided to eat it at the hotel pool while enjoying the sunshine. Immediately a pool waiter told my brother that we had to move to the beach (incidentally the pool area was only 30 % full at this point of the day) My brother and I refused since we were paying guests at the hotel, we figured this is obsurd, as this occurred, we continued to eat our bagels. Soon security was called and we found ourselves surrounded by 3 security officers, two uniformed, one in a suit, the bar manager, and the bar waiter. I asked  what's the problem One of the security guards replied that our eating of food at the pool not purchased at the Wyndham was against hotel policy I replied that it was against my own policy to pay for a room that was dusty, had a leaky air conditioner, and a out of order cordless phone. We continued to eat as they tried to determine how to handle the situation. I actually feared that they would attempt to bodily remove us from the pool area.( the suited guy was big!!!) I finally stated to the bar manager that they were all beginning to look foolish. (as I took my last bite of my bagel) I told the bar manager that the way that I would have solved this was to politely ask the person eating to finish up and dont do it again for the rest of the stay. She agreed. ( she was reasonable and polite) The bar waiter then used profanity without provocation. Incidentally no one really knew where our food had been purchased of them since the bakery used plain white bags and generic coffee cups. The security staff then scattered and I left the pool area while being stared at by all of the other guests. I announced to all of them that I was only guilty of bringing outside food, thats all. ( If I had winessed the response, I would have assumed that the perps were doing drugs or something!!) Most seemed surprised by the response of the staff. I promptly went straight to management and was given a hollow apology and was told that my AC leak and cordless phone would be fixed. Neither was, they simply unplugged the phone. I promptly called Wyndham and explained my situation, they said they would address the situation ( I phoned Dallas headquarters) Needless to say that was the end of my dealings with any management. We later found out that a bagel and coffee in a plain white bag with OJ could have been purchased from the hotel, that there was no way they could have known it was from outside unless we admitted it or failed to show a receipt. On our last day of our stay we repeated our sequence , this time purchasing all from the hotel premises. My brother was stopped and checked prior to entering the pool area AFTER purchasing these items from the hotel. He promptly shoved the receipt into the guards face. I also witnessed them pointing at us repeatedly during our stay at the hotel when we went in the pool area. What bothered me most about all of this was that THERE WERE NO WRITTEN RULES ANYWHERE to tell the guest that eating off-site food in public areas was not allowed. This hotel has the most unruly, unwelcoming staff at any hotel, cruiseship, BB that I have ever stayed. I was actually was glad to leave this most unfriendly and over-priced hotel. I stayed at Howard Johnsons 4 months prior and had a better experience, cleaner and better appointed rooms with a better view of the ocean for half the price. It was the first time I was glad to return to Michigan after a stay in the tropics. Stay away, stay away, stay away!!!!! 
