<Content>No Praise for Wyndham Anyone who has given this hotel a good rating must have been drunk their entire vacation. When I started staying at the El San Juan, it was managed by the Williams Hospitality Group, and it was, without a doubt, the most elegant hotel in the Isla Verde/Condado area. It was spotless, inside and out, and the service was warm and personal. Since Wyndham took over management, the hotel has changed for the worse. I was there in November, and I experienced the same check-in problems as other reviewers. I arrived 12:00 noon and finally got into my room at 5:00 P.M. The 'pager' sure was a waste of time. I have found the last few years that many of the employees have been rude. Surely no one cared that we waited all afternoon to get the room. In fact, when we complained at 4:30 P.M.,the front desk person said the hotel has until 5:00 P.M. to get the room ready. Rude? You bet. Our room was O.K., and when I spotted the coffee set-up, I was anxious to have a cup of coffee. By the way, Puerto Rican coffee is one of the best coffees in the world. When I looked closer at the coffeemaker, there was about a quarter of a pot of coffee left in the carafe, and it was molded! How long had that been sitting there? I lost my taste for coffee. I later requested a clean carafe, but believe it or not, that same carafe (with the molded coffee) remained in the room for the four days I was there - proof that the rooms aren't cleaned too often. Two years ago the concierge booked the wrong restaurant for my daughter and her husband, and shrugged and said, so go to the one I booked. Acouple of years ago my friends were at the pool area without their pool wrist bands, and were treated like criminals by the Security force. I could go on and on, but you get the idea. Maybe these misses don't seem too important, but I've never paid under $300.00 for a night at this hotel, and so I would expect much better treatment. Why return? It's like everyone says, the pool area and 